Peritoneal dialysis access: a comparison of peritoneoscopic and surgical 
insertion techniques.

Eklund B(1), Groop PH, Halme L, Honkanen E, Kala AR.

Author information:
(1)Department of Surgery, Helsinki University Central Hospital, Finland.

Prospectively collected data were analysed comparing 108 consecutive 
peritoneoscopically (n = 65) and surgically (n = 43) placed peritoneal dialysis 
catheters during a three-year period. Catheter-linked mechanical complications 
occurred more often in the peritoneoscopical group, and pericatheteral leakage 
ended in catheter loss in 13.8%. Overall probability of catheter survival in the 
peritoneoscopic group at 12, 24 and 36 months was 73%, 56% and 24%, and in the 
