Oxidative damage in the senescence-accelerated mouse.

Mori A(1), Utsumi K, Liu J, Hosokawa M.

Author information:
(1)Okayama University Medical School, Japan.

The senescence-accelerated mouse (SAM) exhibited a shortened life span (about 18 
months) and early manifestation of various signs of senescence, including 
changes in physical activity, skin, and spinal curvature. The mechanism of 
senescence acceleration in SAM is thought to be related to free radical damage. 
Oxidative phosphorylation was estimated in liver mitochondria from SAMPS and the 
senescence-resistant subtrain, SAMR1. The respiratory control ratio decreased 
during aging, and the ATP/O, an index of ATP synthesis, was depressed at 18 
months of age in SAMPS. DNP-dependent uncoupled respiration in liver 
mitochondria was markedly decreased, and active uptake of calcium was markedly 
dysfunctional with aging. These findings suggest that the functional disorders 
in mitochondria may be closely related to the shorter life span of SAMPS. 
White-footed (WF) mice can live at least to 5.5 years, when some animals are 
still capable of reproducing and their external body condition remains healthy. 
The mitochondrial functions were examined in the same way as in the SAM 
experiments. However, no particular finding responsible for their longevity was 
observed in WF mice at 3 and 12 months old. More comprehensive examinations on 
more aged WF mice are needed for explanation of their greater longevity.

